Linux Access Control Review — File Permissions Analysis
Project Overview
As part of a research team at a large organization, I was responsible for ensuring that each team member's access rights were consistent with their job roles and assigned tasks.
This activity involved reviewing existing file and directory permissions and verifying alignment with the least privilege principle. To protect confidential data — such as financial records — from insider threats or external attackers, I modified or removed unauthorized access where necessary.

Check File and Directory Details
Before making any changes, I reviewed the permissions of the /home/researcher2/projects directory using the ls -la command to display file ownership, group ownership, permissions, and hidden files.
This directory contained:

One hidden file (.project_x.txt)
Several project files
A subdirectory called drafts

During this initial review, I identified the following issues:

Inconsistent permissions across files with similar purposes.
Excessive execution permissions on the drafts directory beyond the intended user.
Broader access than expected on certain files.

These observations guided the permission modifications in the following steps.
